The American Meat Institute, AME,said it intended to ask the U.S. government to retaliateagainst a European Community meat inspection requirement.    AME President C. Manly Molpus also said the industry wouldfile a petition challenging Korea's ban of U.S. meat products.    Molpus told a Senate Agriculture subcommittee that AME andother livestock and farm groups intended to file a petitionunder Section 301 of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Tradeagainst an EC directive that, effective April 30, will requireU.S. meat processing plants to comply fully with EC standards.    The meat industry will seek to have the U.S. governmentretaliate against EC and Korean exports if their complaints areupheld. Reuter&#3;